Package: RSurvivEHR
Type: Package
Title: Survival Analysis on Electronic Health Records via SurvivEHR
Version: 0.10.0
Authors@R: person(given = "Pedro", family = "Cardoso", role = c("aut", "cre"),
    email = "p.cardoso@exeter.ac.uk", comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0002-1014-9058"))
Description: An R interface to SurvivEHR (Gadd et al., 2026,
    <doi:10.1038/s41746-026-02709-z>), a GPT-style transformer pre-trained on
    longitudinal Electronic Health Record (EHR) event sequences and fine-tuned
    for time-to-event prediction using neural ordinary differential equation
    survival heads. The package covers the full modelling pipeline: vocabulary
    construction from clinical event histories, backbone pre-training with
    competing-risk or single-risk survival objectives, supervised fine-tuning
    on labelled outcome cohorts, and inference returning cumulative-incidence
    curves at arbitrary time horizons. Static covariates (demographics,
    deprivation indices) are one-hot encoded and fused with the sequence
    representations. Continuous biomarker values (e.g. blood pressure, HbA1c)
    can be modelled alongside discrete events via an auxiliary Gaussian
    regression head. Helper functions enforce leakage-free cohort construction
    and validate input schemas with informative R-level errors. All input
    accepts plain R data frames; the Python backend is vendored inside the
    package and managed automatically via 'reticulate'.
